<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-447-301  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 447 301.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Sept 17 1990 n287 p38(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Automation turns gold: Copperweld's automated factory links salesand floor staff.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Krass, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>$300 million bimetallic wire and tubing manufacturer CopperweldCorp built a fully automated plant in Birmingham, AL, in only fivemonths.andP;  The $800,000 automation project for the $20 million plantwas carried out by software vendor MPACT (Brookfield, WI) andTandem Computers Inc (Cupertino, CA), which provided its VLXcomputers.andP;  (The two firms previously automated Copperweld'sShelby, OH, plant.) MPACT provided its SmartCASE computer-aidedsoftware engineering system; InterACT set of business andmanufacturing applications; and a team of programmers to tailorthe software to Copperweld's needs.andP;  They rapidly createdapplications for such functions as engineering records management,inventory control, purchasing, picking, shipping, order entry,master scheduling, load leveling, materials tracking, costanalysis and accounting functions.andP;  The Birmingham plant wasprofitable after three months.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Copperweld Corp. (management).andO;Ticker:    COS.andO;Topic:     Metal IndustriesAutomationIntegrated SystemsSystem DevelopmentCost Benefit AnalysisManufacturingFactory Management.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablephotograph.andO;Caption:   Companies building computer-integrated factories. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>